  "pride_metadata": {
    "project": {
      "accession": "PXD019861",
      "title": "Proteomic analysis of mycelial exudate of Ustilaginoidea virens",
      "additionalAttributes": [],
      "projectDescription": "Rice false smut (RFS) is a kind of fungal disease transforming panicles and spikelets into greenish spore balls, caused by Ustilaginoidea virens. During artificial cultivation process, macroscopic exudates could be observed, which is a common feature in many kinds of fungi. We characterized the proteome of exudate associated with this plant pathogen. Liquid chromatography-tandem mass spectrometry (LC-MS/MS) analysis was used to identify proteins in the pathogen exudate. A total of 685 proteins comprising 3,949 peptides were identified from the exudate. This study regarded the biological characteristics of U. virens as an entry point. By studying the protein components of the exudates of U. virens, it is helpful to better understand the occurrence and pathogenic mechanism of pathogen and provide a theoretical basis for the control of RFS.",
      "sampleProcessingProtocol": "The three representative U. virens strains (SyUv-01, DdUv-05 and PjUv-07) used in this study were isolated from infected Oryza sativa in Shenyang, Dandong and Panjin of Liaoning Province of China, respectively. The isolates were placed in potato sucrose agar (PSA) medium at 25 \u00b1 1\u00b0C. After 5 days cultivation, the mycelium on the outer edge of the colony was picked up by inoculation needle into a new PSA medium. After the isolates were cultured on the new PSA medium for 25 days, the exudate was collected from the mycelium. The exudate sample was stored in a 1.5 mL tube (Sangon Biotech, Shanghai, China) and quickly passed through liquid nitrogen, then stored at -80\u2103.",
      "dataProcessingProtocol": "Liquid chromatography-tandem mass spectrometry (LC-MS/MS) analysis The peptide segments of the sample were separated by Q Exactive Plus mass spectrometer that was coupled to Easy nLC (Thermo Scientific). Peptide was first loaded to a trap column (100 \u03bcm*20 mm, 5 \u03bcm, C18, Dr. Maisch GmbH, Ammerbuch, Germany) and passed through chromatographic analysis column (75 \u00b5m*150 mm, 3 \u00b5m, C18, Dr. Maisch GmbH, Ammerbuch, Germany) for gradient separation at a flow rate of 300 nl/min. The gradient was set as following: 3% to 8% buffer B (0.1% formic acid) from 0 min to 2min, 8% to 26% buffer B from 2 min to 170 min, 26% to 40% buffer B from 170 min to 206 min, 40% to 100% buffer B from 206 min to 216 min, 100% buffer B kept till to 240 min. The peptide segments were separated by a Q-Exactive Plus mass spectrometer (Thermo Scientific) for DDA (data-dependent acquisition) mass spectrometry analysis. MS data was acquired using a data-dependent top 20 method dynamically choosing the most abundant precursor ions from the survey scan (350-1800 m/z) for HCD fragmentation. The full MS scans were acquired at a resolution of 70,000 at m/z 200, and 17,500 at m/z 200 for MS/MS scan. The maximum injection time of MS and MS/MS were both set to 50 ms. Normalized collision energy was 27 and the isolation window was set to 2.0 Th. Sequence Database Searching The MS data were analyzed using MaxQuant software version 1.6.1.0. MS data were searched against the UniProtKB U. virens database. The trypsin was seleted as digestion enzyme. The maximal two missed cleavage sites and the mass tolerance of 4.5 ppm for precursor ions and 20 ppm for fragment ions were defined for database search. Carbamidomethylation of cysteines was defined as fixed modification, while acetylation of protein N-terminal, oxidation of Methionine were set as variable modifications for database searching. The database search results were filtered and exported with <1% false discovery rate (FDR) at peptide-spectrum-matched level, and protein level, respectively.",
      "projectTags": [],
      "keywords": [
        "Exudate; ustilaginoidea virens;lc-ms"
      ],
      "doi": "",
      "submissionType": "PARTIAL",
